06414nam a22009375i 9789048535873DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20192019ne     fo  d z      eng d  a97890485358737 a10.1515/97890485358732doi  a(DE-B1597)545042  a(OCoLC)1142189959  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anecNL 7aARC0020002bisacsh04a745.449400aOrnament and Monstrosity in Early Modern Art /ced. by Chris Askholt Hammeken, Maria Fabricius Hansen. 1aAmsterdam : bAmsterdam University Press, c[2019] 4c©2019  a1 online resource (282 p.) :b89  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aVisual and Material Culture, 1300 -1700 ;v1300tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tList of Illustrations -- tIntroduction -- tPart I. Grotesques -- t1. Ambiguous Delights: Ornamental Grotesques and Female Monstrosity in Sixteenth-Century Italy -- t2. Dissonant Symphonies: The Villa d'Este in Tivoli and the Grotesque -- tPart II. Sacred Space and Narrative -- t3. Outside-In: The Intrusion of Ornament into Sacred Narrative -- t4. 'That savage should mate with tame': Hybridity, Indeterminacy, and the Grotesque in the Murals of San Miguel Arcángel (Ixmiquilpan, Mexico) -- t5. Decoration in the Desert: Unsettling the Order of Architecture in the Certosa di San Martino -- tPart III. Agency and Ornament Enlivened -- t6. Masquing/(Un)Masking: Animation and the Restless Ornament of Fontainebleau -- t7. Sea-Change: The Whale in the Florentine Loggia -- t8. Ornament and Agency: Vico's Poetic Monsters -- tPart IV. A Historical Perspective -- t9. Trafficking the Body: Prolegomena to a Posthumanist Theory of Ornament and Monstrosity -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aEarly modern art features a remarkable fascination with ornament, both as decorative device and compositional strategy, across artistic media and genres. Interestingly, the inventive, elegant manifestations of ornament in the art of the period often include layers of disquieting paradoxes, creating tensions - monstrosities even - that manifest themselves in a variety of ways. In some cases, dichotomies (between order and chaos, artificiality and nature, rational logic and imaginative creativity, etc.) may emerge. Elsewhere, a sense of agitation undermines structures of statuesque control or erupts into wild, unruly displays of constant genesis. The monstrosity of ornament is brought into play through strategies of hybridity and metamorphosis, or by the handling of scale, proportion, and space in ambiguous and discomforting ways that break with the laws of physical reality. An interest in strange exaggeration and curious artifice allows for such colossal ornamental attitude to thrive within early modern art.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 4aArt and Material Culture. 4aEarly Modern Studies. 4aHistory, Art History, and Archaeology. 4aHistory. 7aARCHITECTURE / Decoration & Ornament.2bisacsh  aEarly modern and Renaissance art, artificiality, playfulness, ambiguity, anxiety, ornament.1 aAndersen, Lisa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAristova, Maria-Anna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAskholt Hammeken, Chris, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aConnelly, Frances, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFabricius Hansen, Maria, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHammeken, Chris Askholt, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHansen, Maria Fabricius, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHelena Uchacz, Tianna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMorgan, Luke, eco